BYD, China Eastern, China Shipping, SAIC: China Equity Preview

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-07-07T00:22:31Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-06/byd-construction-bank-eastern-airlines-china-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies may
have unusual moves in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the previous close, unless
stated otherwise.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, dropped 0.2 percent to 2,810.48. The
 CSI 300 Index (SHSZ300)  fell 0.3 percent to 3,113.71.  China raised benchmark  interest rates  for the third time
this year. The one-year lending rate will increase to 6.56
percent from 6.31 percent today, the People’s Bank of China said
on its website yesterday. The one-year deposit rate rises to 3.5
percent from 3.25 percent.  BYD Co. (002594 CH): The automaker part-owned by  Warren Buffett ’s Berkshire Hathaway Inc. said its June vehicle sales
fell 8 percent from a year earlier to 32,515 units. The shares
rose 1.1 percent to 33.4 yuan.  China Eastern  Airlines Corp. (600115 CH): China’s top
economic planning body approved plans by the nation’s third-
largest carrier by market value to bring 16 airplanes into the
country through overseas financing. The shares rose 1.7 percent
to 5.35 yuan.  China Gezhouba Group Co. (600068 CH): The builder of
hydropower projects plans to sell 2 billion yuan ($309 million)
of 1-year bonds on July 13. The shares added 0.2 percent to
12.25 yuan.  China Shipping Development Co. (600026 CH): The unit of
China’s second-biggest sea-cargo group won China Securities
Regulatory Commission approval to issue as much as 3.95 billion
yuan of convertible bonds. The shares fell 0.6 percent to 8.51
yuan.  Industrial & Commercial Bank of China (601398)  Ltd. (601398 CH): The
Australian unit of China’s biggest lender sold A$400 million
($428 million) of three-year bonds. The shares fell 0.9 percent
to 4.37 yuan.  SAIC Motor Corp. (600104 CH): China’s largest carmaker said
first-half sales increased 13 percent to about 2 million units.
The shares lost 1.2 percent to 19.14 yuan.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
